Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the U.S. government represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had continued to balloon in light of falling house prices.
Now that the government is fully responsible for Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac's debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that is not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most openly capitalist country in the world?
Don't the venerable principles of capitalism not include that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers now have to suffer the consequences of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral issues of the current financial crisis were clearly outlined.
But they are not.
What is unclear, above all, is whether the bailout will actually cost American taxpayers anything in the end. It may prevent further systemic effects that would cripple the financial sector—and thus the global economy.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
Moreover, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as implicitly guaranteed by the U.S. government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the failure of the U.S. government to carry out a rescue operation could undermine confidence in government securities—and because they are linked to these—also in other financial assets.
The problems extend far beyond the U.S. economy.
In recent years, the world economy has been driven by remarkable speculative highs and crashes in asset values, introducing questions of trust, as well as fairness, into the equation.
In many other countries as well, similar boom periods in the housing sector are currently coming to an end, and they may now be facing the same hardships – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not just the housing markets.
The stock markets are as well.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose fivefold between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose 5 times in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar highs and crashes in the stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they persisted, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating of these economies.
Well, now that they have turned around, a loss of confidence could grip the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary—not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when help fails to arrive in the face of collapsing markets.
People's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and their sense of justice.
The described ups and downs have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested on the stock market or in the real estate market did well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will assess the fairness of these results based on what they were told and the silent promises they inferred from it.
What were the people in all these countries told about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find that out.
Politics can only react in general and cannot deal with each case individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times has been spectacular in many countries.
But were the capital investments in their markets sold too expensively?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
One thing is certain: although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice given with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not struggling with hunger.
Yet we cannot carelessly conclude from this that all their losses should be left entirely untouched.
The gnawing problem is one of "good faith."
Economies flourish only when "honesty and faith" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative euphoria has driven the world economy – and now, after its collapse, is driving it into recession – suggests that people who have promoted certain capital investments have done so contrary to good faith.
Take the investors who have purchased bonds from Fannie and Freddie.
Although the U.S. government never officially promised to come to their aid in times of need, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
But this agency has never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The top officials of the government never issued a warning.
Can we therefore really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is beginning to discover the power of capitalism to transform economies.
Yet capitalism relies on trust.
A perceived unfair treatment can be deadly for economic growth, as it means people lose trust in companies and are therefore less willing to provide them with their valuable capital and labor.
Is a result such as this morally preferable to a bailout?
